    <stitle>13 SPEED AND 18 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS EATON RTLO-713/18 SERIES - REMOVE - COUNTERSHAFT BEARINGS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="7">
        <title>COUNTERSHAFT BEARINGS</title>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>The following instructions are used to remove the upper and lower countershaft bearings. To remove
                    the mainshaft assembly, only the upper countershaft bearings need to be removed.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Performing the following instructions will damage the bearings and should not be done unless
                    bearing replacement is planned.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>The bearing inner race remains pressed on the countershaft after removal of the front bearings.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the snap ring from each countershaft rear groove (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300742">Figure 42</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300742" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300742" filename="../figg13/G1300742.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 42. Remove Snap Ring From Countershaft Rear Groove</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">From inside the case, use a soft bar and maul to drive the countershaft rear bearings from
                the case bores (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300743">Figure 43</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300743" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300743" filename="../figg13/G1300743.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 43. Drive Countershaft Rear Bearings From Case Bores</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the bolt and front retainer plate from each countershaft (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300744">Figure 44</hotlnk>and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300745">Figure 45</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300744" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300744" filename="../figg13/G1300744.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 44. Remove Bolt From Each Countershaft</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f1300745" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300745" filename="../figg13/G1300745.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 45. Remove Front Retainer Plate From Each Countershaft</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use the soft bar and maul to drive each countershaft to the rear as far as possible (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300746">Figure 46</hotlnk>). This partially unseats the front bearings.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300746" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300746" filename="../figg13/G1300746.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 46. Drive Each Countershaft To Rear</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Return to the case rear, and drive each countershaft forward as far as possible (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300747">Figure 47</hotlnk>). This exposes the bearing snap rings.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300747" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300747" filename="../figg13/G1300747.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 47. Drive Each Countershaft Forward</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a bearing puller or pry bars to remove the countershaft front bearings (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300748">Figure 48</hotlnk>). If a bearing puller is used, the front bearing cover has
                to be removed.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300748" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300748" filename="../figg13/G1300748.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 48. Remove Countershaft Front Bearings</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
